<hl>
<seg id=1> Thailand Welcomes Khieu Samlphan's Surrender </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> Bangkok journalist Liu Zhenting reports </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> Thai government yesterday expressed welcome to the surrender of Khmer Rouge's two important members Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea to the Phnom Penh Authorities. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> Foreign Ministry Spokesperson Gu Sa said at the press conference, "the surrender of Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea will be an important event for Kambodia's realization of ethnic conciliations and efforts to end internal conflicts. This will not only bring peace to Cambodia but also stabilize the regional situation." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> Gu Sa reiterated that Thailand will never support any party of Cambodia to participate in an activity of subverting a neighboring country by taking advantage of Thailand. </seg>
<seg id=6> Once any foreign armed members are found taking advantage of Thai territory to take part in activities, the Thai side will disarm them and bring them to justice. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> He also said that Thailand in this May signed a criminal extradition agreement with Hon Son government, therefore Thailand can also according to law hand over the wanted persons by Cambodia to the Phnom Penh Authorities for punishment. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> Also, according to a well-informed source in Phnom Penh, Thai Foreign Minister Dr. Su Lin has invited Cambodian Foreign Minister Hor Namhong to visit Bangkok at the beginning next year so as to discuss problems about guaranty of mutual border peace and handling tens of thousands of Cambodian refugees who are still held up within the boundary of Thailand and considered resuming supplying Cambodia with human talents training bailout. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> The Asian summit meeting held in Hanoi in the middle of this month once decided to accept Cambodia as the 10th member country of Asia Safety Association and authorized ASA Foreign Minister to prepare the ceremony for officially welcoming Cambodia's entry into the Association in Hanoi. </seg>
</p>
